20 arcsec. For sources above the ATATS completeness\nlimit, the median flux density is 97% of the median value for matched NVSS\nsources, indicative of an accurate overall flux calibration. We examine the\neffects of source confusion due to the effects of differing resolution between\nATATS and NVSS on our ability to compare flux densities. We detect no\ntransients at flux densities greater than 40 mJy in comparison with NVSS, and\nplace a 2-sigma upper limit on the transient rate for such sources of 0.004 per\nsquare degree. These results suggest that the > 1 Jy transients reported by\nMatsumura et al. (2009) may not be true transients, but rather variable sources\nat their flux density threshold.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 10 Jun 2010 11:01:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 11 Jun 2010 15:05:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-19"}
{"id":"1006.2004","submitter":"Georg Bocherer","authors":"Georg Bocherer and Rudolf Mathar","title":"Throughput, Bit-Cost, Network State Information: Tradeoffs in\n  Cooperative CSMA Protocols","comments":"Some typos in v1 were corrected, to be presented at ISWCS 2010 in\n  York, United Kingdom","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.IT math.IT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In wireless local area networks, spatially varying channel conditions result\nin a severe performance discrepancy between different nodes in the uplink,\ndepending on their position. Both throughput and energy expense are affected.\nCooperative protocols were proposed to mitigate these discrepancies. However,\nadditional network state information (NSI) from other nodes is needed to enable\ncooperation. The aim of this work is to assess how NSI and the degree of\ncooperation affect throughput and energy expenses. To this end, a CSMA protocol\ncalled fairMAC is defined, which allows to adjust the amount of NSI at the\nnodes and the degree of cooperation among the nodes in a distributed manner. By\nanalyzing the data obtained by Monte Carlo simulations with varying protocol\nparameters for fairMAC, two fundamental tradeoffs are identified: First, more\ncooperation leads to higher throughput, but also increases energy expenses.\nSecond, using more than one helper increases throughput and decreases energy\nexpenses, however, more NSI has to be acquired by the nodes in the network. The\nobtained insights are used to increase the lifetime of a network. While full\ncooperation shortens the lifetime compared to no cooperation at all, lifetime\ncan be increased by over 25% with partial cooperation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 10 Jun 2010 11:23:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 21 Jun 2010 12:28:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2010-06-22"}
